Example 1: Dynamic cursor with table name parameter

```sql
CREATE OR REPLACE PROCEDURE getEmployeeDetails(tab_name IN VARCHAR2) IS
    emp_id NUMBER;
    emp_name VARCHAR2(100);
    emp_salary NUMBER;
    CURSOR emp_cursor IS
        EXECUTE IMMEDIATE 'SELECT employee_id, employee_name, salary FROM ' || tab_name;
BEGIN
    OPEN emp_cursor;

    LOOP
        FETCH emp_cursor INTO emp_id, emp_name, emp_salary;
        EXIT WHEN emp_cursor%NOTFOUND;

        DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Employee ID: ' || emp_id || ', Name: ' || emp_name || ', Salary: ' || emp_salary);
    END LOOP;

    CLOSE emp_cursor;
END;
```

In this example, the procedure `getEmployeeDetails` accepts a table name as a parameter. The `EXECUTE IMMEDIATE` statement dynamically constructs a SELECT statement based on the table name parameter. The cursor `emp_cursor` is then opened, and the employee details are fetched one by one using the FETCH statement. The employee ID, name, and salary are printed using `DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE`.

Example 2: Dynamic PL/SQL block execution

```sql
CREATE OR REPLACE PROCEDURE executeDynamicBlock(block_body IN VARCHAR2) IS
BEGIN
    EXECUTE IMMEDIATE 'BEGIN ' || block_body || ' END;';

    DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Dynamic PL/SQL block executed successfully.');
END;
```

In this example, the procedure `executeDynamicBlock` accepts a PL/SQL block body as a parameter. The `EXECUTE IMMEDIATE` statement executes the dynamic PL/SQL block. This allows you to execute any valid PL/SQL code provided as the parameter.

